"""
MKT Context Commentary — John chapters 14–16
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-john-14-16.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/john.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/john.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-context/john.json (prior chapters for continuity)
- data/commentary/ellicott/john.json (philological background)

Key decisions in this range:
- "The Evangelist" throughout (following established pattern)
- Farewell discourse genre: Second Temple Jewish testament literature as primary frame (chs 14–16)
- Paraclete/paraklētos: legal and pastoral sense both noted; Qumran "spirit of truth" as closest parallel
- "Spirit of truth" (14:17): 1QS 3:18–26 two-spirit doctrine cited as background, not source
- "Prince of this world": Second Temple Jewish angelology (Belial, Eph 2:2) as frame
- Vine imagery (15:1): treated as deliberate claim to be true Israel against OT vine-failure texts
- aposynagogos (16:2): Birkat ha-Minim context noted as plausible but historically debated
- Birth pangs (16:21): hevlei ha-mashiah rabbinic term and Qumran Hodayot parallel cited
- 14:28 "Father is greater than I": pastoral context prioritized; later Arian controversy noted briefly
- Zech 13:7 allusion at 16:32: noted because the Synoptics make the citation explicit
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html


JOHN = {
  "14": {
    "1": '<p>The discourse opens in the Passover meal context and belongs to a well-established literary genre in Second Temple Judaism: the farewell discourse or "testament," in which a dying figure instructs successors, predicts future challenges, and exhorts faithfulness. The Testaments of the Twelve Patriarchs, the Testament of Moses, and similar texts follow this pattern; the audience familiar with such texts would have recognized the literary frame immediately. Jesus\'s opening command — "Do not let your hearts be troubled" — echoes the consolation language of the psalms of trust (Ps 42:5, 11; 43:5) and reframes what follows not as tragedy but as prepared departure.</p>',

    "2": '<p>"My Father\'s house has many rooms" — the word <em>monē</em> (dwelling place, room) appears only here and in verse 23 in the NT. "Father\'s house" in this Gospel was used for the Temple in Jerusalem (2:16); its application here to the heavenly realm reflects Second Temple Jewish cosmology. 1 Enoch describes multiple heavens with distinct regions (chs. 14, 17–18); the Apocalypse of Baruch and other texts elaborate a "palace" or "house" of God in which the righteous dead await. The promise of a prepared "place" (<em>topos</em>) imports the spatial-heavenly location language familiar from this literature into the language of personal relationship between Jesus and his disciples.</p>',

    "3": '<p>The image of Jesus departing to prepare a dwelling and then returning to take the disciples there carried structural resonance in Jewish wedding custom, where the bridegroom prepared the bridal chamber in his father\'s house before returning to bring his bride. More broadly, the pattern of the patron who goes ahead to secure provision for his household before returning to gather them was recognizable within the honor-client framework. Both registers — marital and patronal — would have been available to the first audience; the Evangelist leaves the resonances active without specifying which is primary.</p>',

    "4": '<p>"You know the way" — the claim is answered by Thomas\'s puzzlement in verse 5 and produces the sixth "I am" declaration. Significantly, the early Christian movement identified itself as "the Way" (<em>hē hodos</em>) in the early chapters of Acts (Acts 9:2; 19:9, 23; 24:14, 22). The Dead Sea Scrolls community similarly used way-language for its sectarian path, drawing on Isa 40:3 ("prepare the way of the LORD in the wilderness"). Jesus\'s claim to be the Way draws on the same prophetic tradition but identifies the person rather than the community practice as the path.</p>',

    "5": '<p>Thomas\'s inability to follow Jesus\'s directional language is characteristic of the pattern the Evangelist has established throughout: disciples, like Nicodemus and the Samaritan woman, consistently hear Jesus\'s words at the literal or material level before the spiritual meaning opens to them. Thomas, established in chapter 11 as the disciple willing to die with Jesus but uncertain about transcendent realities, serves here as the voice of literal-minded engagement. The Evangelist uses his question not to blame him but to create the space for the "I am the way" declaration.</p>',

    "6": '<p>"I am the way and the truth and the life" — the claim to be "the way" in a Jewish context was radical because the Torah itself was described as "the way of life" in Deuteronomy (Deut 30:15–20), and personified Wisdom in Proverbs is the path to life (Prov 8). Jesus\'s claim to BE the way, rather than to teach it, places him in the position occupied by Torah and Wisdom in Jewish religious thought. Second Temple Jewish literature (Sirach, the Wisdom of Solomon) had extended the Wisdom of Proverbs into cosmic and salvific categories; the Evangelist presents Jesus as the reality those categories were pointing toward.</p>',

    "7": '<p>"From now on, you do know him and have seen him" — the perfect-tense claim (<em>eorakate</em>, "you have seen") is startling given that Philip\'s request in verse 8 shows the disciples do not feel they have seen the Father. The Evangelist\'s realized eschatology is at work: the disclosure of the Father has already occurred in Jesus\'s ministry, whether or not the disciples have yet understood it. The pattern matches 2:22 and 12:16: understanding comes retrospectively, after the events have occurred and the Spirit has opened the meaning.</p>',

    "8": '<p>Philip\'s request "Show us the Father" echoes Moses\'s petition in Exod 33:18 ("Show me your glory") — the foundational theophany-seeking moment of Israel\'s history, answered by God passing before Moses while Moses was hidden in the rock cleft. The tradition of direct divine encounter sought by Israel\'s great figures (Moses, Elijah in 1 Kgs 19) is the background against which Philip\'s request should be heard. Jesus\'s response claims to surpass what was given even to Moses: those who have seen the Son have seen more than Moses saw, because in the Son the Father is fully present.</p>',

    "9": '<p>Philip had been with Jesus from the beginning of the public ministry (1:43–45) and had been present at all the signs. The Evangelist has characterized Philip as the disciple who thinks quantitatively and practically (6:5–7, the feeding calculation; 12:21–22, managing the Greeks\' request to see Jesus). His failure to perceive the revelation of the Father in Jesus is not a moral failure but a failure of the kind of spiritual recognition the Prologue describes as universal: "He was in the world... the world did not know him" (1:10–11). The same light that illuminates is not always seen as light.</p>',

    "10": '<p>The mutual indwelling of Father and Son is articulated in terms of works rather than metaphysical essence: the Father, "living in me, doing his work." This is significant for a Jewish audience for whom works were the primary medium of divine character disclosure — God was known through his mighty acts (Ps 77:11–12; Isa 28:21; the Psalms of praise for God\'s deeds). The claim is not philosophical abstraction but observable reality: the works Jesus performs are the Father\'s works, making the Father visible to those with eyes to see.</p>',

    "11": '<p>The appeal to "the evidence of the works themselves" as grounds for belief maps onto the Jewish requirement that a prophet be validated by the correspondence of his words and deeds. Deut 18:21–22 provides the criterion; more immediately, the works Jesus has done — turning water to wine, feeding thousands, healing the blind man born blind, raising Lazarus — are an evidentiary case. The Evangelist has presented them precisely as signs that testify to Jesus\'s identity; v11 makes the apologetic function explicit.</p>',

    "12": '<p>"Greater works than these" — interpreted in the context of the early church\'s mission, the "greater works" were the worldwide spread of the gospel, geographically and numerically exceeding the scope of Jesus\'s own ministry in Galilee and Judea. Acts presents the fulfillment of this promise: from Jerusalem to Judea and Samaria to the ends of the earth (Acts 1:8). In the Johannine framework, the works done through the Paraclete after Jesus\'s departure are the continuation and extension of the Son\'s mission through his representative community.</p>',

    "13": '<p>Prayer "in the name" of a divine agent was not unique to Christianity — Jewish intercessory texts sometimes invoked mediating figures, and the magical papyri made regular use of divine names as addresses of power. But the Johannine "in my name" is different from a formula: it describes a state of alignment with Jesus\'s own will and character, asking as Jesus would ask. The name carries the full identity of the person; to ask in Jesus\'s name is to ask within the framework of his revealed purpose, not to append a phrase to a petition.</p>',

    "14": '<p>The promise is repeated with emphasis on the pronoun "I" (<em>egō</em>): "I will do it." The expectation of answered prayer in Second Temple Judaism was generally directed to God the Father, with intercession sometimes routed through angels or righteous humans. The claim that the Son himself answers prayer places Jesus in the position that prayer addresses — a significant step in the Gospel\'s Christological development. The parallel in 16:23 will adjust the emphasis: the Father also answers prayer made in the Son\'s name.</p>',

    "15": '<p>"If you love me, keep my commands" — the conditional structure exactly mirrors the Deuteronomic covenant logic: love the LORD your God, therefore keep his commandments (Deut 6:5–6; 10:12–13; 11:1). The Shema itself binds love and obedience together: love is expressed through commandment-keeping, and keeping the commandments deepens love. The Johannine command-keeping is not legalism but covenant loyalty — the outward form of a prior inward relationship. The same logic appears in 1 John 5:3: "This is love for God: to keep his commands."</p>',

    "16": '<p>The Greek <em>paraklētos</em> appears only in the Johannine literature (John 14:16, 26; 15:26; 16:7; and of Jesus in 1 John 2:1). The word combines legal and pastoral senses: a <em>paraklete</em> was one called alongside (<em>para</em> + <em>klētos</em>) to help — whether as a legal defense advocate in a court proceeding, or as a personal counselor and intercessor in a crisis. In Hellenistic legal practice, a wealthy patron might serve as a paraklete for a client, using his social standing to advocate before a tribunal. The Evangelist\'s "another advocate" (allon paraklēton) implies that Jesus himself is the first, as 1 John 2:1 confirms: "we have an advocate with the Father — Jesus Christ the Righteous One."</p>',

    "17": '<p>"Spirit of truth" — the phrase appears in the Community Rule from Qumran (1QS 3:18–26), where the "spirit of truth" and the "spirit of deceit" are the two cosmic forces that divide humanity. The Qumran community\'s sharp dualism between truth and falsehood, light and darkness, is the closest Jewish parallel to the Johannine usage. Both bodies of literature present the spirit of truth as the inner resource enabling the community to live faithfully against the world\'s opposition. The difference is significant: in Qumran, the two spirits are semi-personified cosmic forces; in John, the Spirit of truth is the personal divine presence — the Paraclete who will dwell in the disciples themselves.</p>',

    "18": '<p>"Orphans" (<em>orphanous</em>) — the metaphor carries full social weight. In Roman-era Jewish society, an orphan was among the most legally and economically exposed persons: without a father\'s patronage, an orphan lacked a court advocate, had no inheritance claims without specific provision, and had reduced social standing. The OT consistently identifies God as the "father of orphans" and calls the community to care for them (Ps 68:5; Deut 10:18; Isa 1:17). The promise "I will not leave you as orphans" invokes both the social vulnerability of the abandoned and the theological tradition of God as protector of the fatherless — placing the disciples under that same divine care.</p>',

    "19": '<p>"The world will not see me anymore, but you will see me" — the double horizon is characteristic of the farewell discourse: the immediate future (death and resurrection appearances within days) and the long-term post-Easter reality. Jewish eschatological expectation associated the absence of the divine presence (the Shekinah departing the Temple at the exile: Ezek 10–11) with devastation; the departure of the Shekinah was the interpretive category for Israel\'s disasters. Here the departure is temporary and purposeful — not abandonment but strategic withdrawal preceding a fuller coming.</p>',

    "20": '<p>"That day" in prophetic literature was the Day of the LORD (<em>yôm YHWH</em>), the time of divine intervention that would bring both judgment and restoration (Isa 2:11–12; Amos 5:18–20; Joel 2:1–2, 31). The Evangelist transfers the phrase to the day of the Spirit\'s coming (Pentecost as its primary fulfillment) and to the ongoing experience of the indwelling Spirit — the realized eschatology characteristic of this Gospel. The mutual indwelling described ("you are in me, and I am in you") is the personal realization of what the prophets associated with the end-time.</p>',

    "21": '<p>The chain of love — obedience → Father\'s love → Jesus\'s love → personal self-disclosure — mirrors the covenantal logic of Deuteronomy (faithfulness → divine blessing) but has transformed its content: the terminus is personal encounter with the risen Christ rather than national prosperity or long life in the land. The self-disclosure (<em>emphanizō</em>, "show myself") recalls the theophany tradition (Exod 33:13 LXX: Moses asks God to "show" him his ways). Jesus\'s promise is that the intimate encounter that Moses sought God will grant to those who love the Son.</p>',

    "22": '<p>Judas (not Iscariot) is commonly identified with Lebbaeus/Thaddaeus in the Synoptic apostle lists (Luke 6:16: "Judas son of James"; Acts 1:13). The question he poses — why show yourself to us and not to the world? — expresses the conventional messianic expectation of a public and political disclosure. The texts of Second Temple Jewish messianism (Psalms of Solomon 17; 4 Ezra 7:28–29; the War Scroll 1QM) consistently envision the Messiah\'s coming as a triumphant public event visible to the nations. Jesus\'s answer refuses this framework: the criterion for the divine self-disclosure is love, not national or political categories.</p>',

    "23": '<p>"We will come to them and make our home with them" — the word <em>monē</em> (home, dwelling) used here echoes verse 2 ("many rooms"). The movement is now reversed: in v2 Jesus goes ahead to prepare a place for the disciples; here, the Father and Son come to make their home with the disciple. The Evangelist holds both movements together: the eschatological dwelling of disciples with God, and the present indwelling of God with disciples. This is the realized eschatology of the Fourth Gospel: the future promise of Rev 21:3 ("God\'s dwelling place is now among the people") is anticipated in the present experience of mutual indwelling through love and obedience.</p>',

    "24": '<p>"These words you hear are not my own; they belong to the Father who sent me" — the legal principle of agency (<em>shaliach</em> in Jewish law) governs Jesus\'s self-presentation throughout the farewell discourse. The shaliach\'s authority was entirely derived from the sender; the shaliach\'s words were the sender\'s words; to receive the shaliach was to receive the sender (cf. 13:20). Jesus\'s consistent appeal to the Father as the source of his words is not false modesty but the claim of a legitimately authorized representative — with the implication that rejecting Jesus\'s words is rejecting the Father\'s.</p>',

    "25": '<p>The transitional marker — "while still with you" (<em>par\' hymin menōn</em>) — signals the shift to the Paraclete section. The discourse is self-aware of its own temporality: Jesus teaches now, while physically present; the Spirit will continue and extend that teaching in his absence. The contrast between presence and absence, speaking now and what the Spirit will do later, frames the Paraclete promises as continuity rather than replacement.</p>',

    "26": '<p>"The Holy Spirit, whom the Father will send in my name, will teach you all things and will remind you of everything I have said" — the Spirit sent "in Jesus\'s name" does not introduce a new revelation beyond Jesus but is the ongoing presence of Jesus\'s teaching in the community. This had significant practical implications for early Christian discernment of spirits (1 John 4:1–3): any spirit that contradicted or moved beyond Jesus\'s teaching could not be the Paraclete sent in his name. The "remind" function (anamimn<em>ēskō</em>) is particularly significant: it accounts for the post-Easter understanding of events that were not understood at the time (2:22; 12:16).</p>',

    "27": '<p>"Peace I leave with you; my peace I give you" — <em>shalom</em> in Hebrew (rendered <em>eirēnē</em> in Greek) served as the standard Jewish greeting and farewell formula, but its semantic range far exceeded social politeness. In the Hebrew Bible, shalom denoted wholeness, covenant status, relational completeness, and the proper ordering of life under God\'s care (Num 6:24–26: the Aaronic benediction culminates in "the LORD give you peace" as the summary of complete divine blessing). The pax Romana — the world\'s peace — was maintained by military force and the suppression of opposition. Jesus\'s explicit distinction ("not as the world gives") contrasts covenantal wholeness with peace-through-power.</p>',

    "28": '<p>"The Father is greater than I" — in its pastoral context this statement addresses the disciples\' sorrow by reframing the departure: Jesus is returning to the Father, and the Father\'s greatness is cause for joy, not grief. The functional subordination expressed here belongs to the economy of the incarnate mission — the Son is sent by the Father, goes to the Father, does the Father\'s will — rather than to a statement about eternal nature. The verse became a central proof text in the Arian controversy of the 4th century; orthodox Christology (Nicaea, 325 CE) distinguished the Son\'s voluntary submission in the incarnate mission from any eternal inequality of essence. The Evangelist\'s immediate concern is pastoral, not metaphysical.</p>',

    "29": '<p>"Before it happens, so that when it does happen you will believe" — the predictive function of the farewell discourse mirrors the prophetic tradition\'s authentication criterion: a true prophet\'s predictions come true (Deut 18:21–22). The Evangelist consistently marks fulfilled predictions (2:22; 12:16), and the farewell discourse will be extensively fulfilled in chapters 18–21. The prior disclosure is a pastoral gift: the disciples will not be caught off-guard; the events will confirm the teaching rather than refute it.</p>',

    "30": '<p>"The prince of this world is coming" — the title <em>ho archōn tou kosmou</em> ("ruler/prince of this world") appears three times in John (12:31; 14:30; 16:11). It reflects Second Temple Jewish cosmology in which the present age was governed by hostile supernatural powers. The Dead Sea Scrolls identify Belial as the "prince of the dominion of wickedness" (1QM 17:5–6). Paul speaks of "the god of this age" who blinds minds (2 Cor 4:4) and "the ruler of the kingdom of the air" (Eph 2:2). The convergence of these traditions shows that the belief in a supernatural adversary ruling the present age was widespread in Jewish and early Jewish-Christian thought; Jesus\'s claim that this ruler "has no hold over me" announces the coming decisive conflict.</p>',

    "31": '<p>"Come now; let us leave" — interpreters have long noted the geographical discrepancy: Jesus says "let us leave" but the discourse continues through chapters 15–16 before any movement to Gethsemane is narrated. Solutions include the hypothesis that chapters 15–16 represent a distinct discourse inserted here, or that the group was already moving through Jerusalem\'s streets while speaking. The Evangelist\'s primary concern is not chronological reconstruction but theological staging: the command to rise frames the discourse for the reader as the eve of passion, signaling that what follows is the final teaching before the decisive conflict with "the prince of this world."</p>'
  },

  "15": {
    "1": '<p>"I am the true vine" — the vine was one of the most resonant symbols of Israel in the OT prophetic tradition. Ps 80:8–16 describes Israel as "a vine out of Egypt" planted by God, then abandoned to destruction. Isa 5:1–7, the Parable of the Vineyard, presents Israel as God\'s carefully cultivated vine that produced only wild grapes — ending with God\'s declaration to let the vineyard be destroyed. Jer 2:21 laments that Israel, planted as a "choice vine of sound and reliable stock," has become a "corrupt wild vine." Ezek 15, 17, and 19 use the vine image to pronounce judgment. The claim "I am the true vine" positions Jesus as the genuine Israel — the one who produces what the OT vine consistently failed to bear. Spoken at or immediately after the Passover meal, where the cup of wine and the vine were central, the image would have resonated with vivid sensory immediacy.</p>',

    "2": '<p>"Every branch in me that bears no fruit he cuts off" — the agricultural practice of vine-dressing was familiar throughout Palestine. The Galilean hillsides and the Judean lowlands were active wine-producing regions; the Mishnah devotes extensive discussion to the laws of the vineyard (<em>Kilayim</em>, <em>Sheviit</em>, <em>Peah</em>). The vine-dresser\'s two primary tasks — removing unproductive branches and pruning productive ones — were regular features of agricultural life. The word <em>katharizein</em> (pruning, making clean) used here is the same root as "clean" in verse 3, creating a deliberate wordplay between agricultural and spiritual purification.</p>',

    "3": '<p>"You are already clean because of the word I have spoken to you" — in the Jewish purity framework, ritual cleanness and uncleanness governed access to the Temple, the cult, and communal life. The Pharisees had extended purity regulations to daily activities, including hand-washing and tithing. Jesus\' bypass of the ritual framework — declaring the disciples clean through his word rather than through ritual observance — is consistent with the controversy over hand-washing in the Synoptics (Mark 7:1–23; Matt 15:1–20) and with the entire Johannine emphasis on Jesus\'s word as the agent of transformation (cf. the healing of the nobleman\'s son by a word from a distance, 4:50).</p>',

    "4": '<p>"Remain in me" — the verb <em>menein</em> (to remain, abide, dwell) occurs about 40 times in the Fourth Gospel, making it one of the Evangelist\'s characteristic words. In Jewish thought, God\'s Shekinah presence "dwelt" (<em>shakan</em>) among his people in the Tabernacle and Temple (Exod 25:8; 1 Kgs 8:12–13). The Spirit of God was associated with remaining or resting on anointed figures (Isa 11:2: "The Spirit of the LORD will rest on him"; cf. 1:32–33 in this Gospel, where the Spirit descended and "remained" on Jesus). The invitation to "remain in me" democratizes and personalizes what had been an institutional framework centered on the sanctuary.</p>',

    "5": '<p>"Apart from me you can do nothing" — the categorical negation is striking in a Jewish context where Torah was understood as the comprehensive guide to righteous living. The Pharisaic tradition, the Dead Sea Scrolls community, and mainstream Second Temple Judaism all agreed that the Torah, properly observed, was sufficient for the covenant life. The claim that apart from Jesus nothing of genuine spiritual fruit can be produced displaces Torah as the sufficient source of covenant obedience — a claim consistent with 14:6 ("No one comes to the Father except through me") and with the Pauline argument in Galatians about the insufficiency of the law to produce the righteousness of faith.</p>',

    "6": '<p>"Thrown into the fire and burned" — the image activates several registers simultaneously. The physical practice of burning unproductive vine-wood (attested in Ezek 15:4–7: "Is wood ever taken from it to make anything useful? When it was whole, they could have made nothing from it... It is thrown into the fire and burned") was common knowledge. The geographic association of fire with Gehenna — the Valley of Hinnom south of Jerusalem, historically used for burning waste and associated with judgment in Jewish literature (1 Enoch 27; 54; 90:26–27) — adds eschatological resonance. John the Baptist\'s "unquenchable fire" (Matt 3:12; Luke 3:17) provides the proximate background.</p>',

    "7": '<p>"Ask whatever you wish, and it will be done for you" — the prayer promise conditioned on mutual abiding is a development of the promise in 14:13. The condition "if my words remain in you" identifies the criterion: a mind formed by Jesus\'s teaching is a mind whose desires are progressively shaped by Jesus\'s own will. Jewish wisdom literature recognized that the righteous person\'s will was conformed to God\'s — "Delight in the LORD and he will give you the desires of your heart" (Ps 37:4). The prayer promise is not unconditional but presupposes the deep formation that abiding in Jesus produces.</p>',

    "8": '<p>"To my Father\'s glory, that you bear much fruit" — glorifying God through the fruitfulness of the covenant community echoes the Servant Songs of Isaiah, where the Servant\'s effective mission redounds to God\'s glory (Isa 42:8; 49:3: "He said to me, \'You are my servant, Israel, in whom I will display my splendor\'"). The disciples\' fruitfulness is not merely personal spiritual development but a public demonstration that magnifies the Father — consistent with Matt 5:16 ("let your light shine before others, that they may see your good deeds and glorify your Father in heaven").</p>',

    "9": '<p>"As the Father has loved me, so have I loved you" — the love descends through the chain: Father → Son → disciples. This mirrors the ANE patron-client network, in which honor and provision flow downward through layers of patronage. But the Johannine vision transforms the client-patron dynamic at its core: the disciples are not merely clients but will be called friends (v15), brought into the inner circle of divine love rather than kept at a respectful distance. The chain will be completed in the High-Priestly Prayer (17:23, 26) where Jesus prays that the disciples will share the love the Father has for the Son.</p>',

    "10": '<p>Jesus presents himself as the model of the relationship he is describing: "just as I have kept my Father\'s commands and remain in his love." The pattern of covenant faithfulness — the Son\'s obedience to the Father as the template for the disciples\' obedience to Jesus — is stated explicitly. This is not merely ethical example but ontological participation: the disciples are invited to inhabit the same relationship to Jesus that Jesus inhabits with the Father.</p>',

    "11": '<p>The joy Jesus speaks of is the eschatological joy associated with the coming kingdom in the beatitudes and in the parables of the talents and the wedding feast (Matt 25:21, 23: "enter into your master\'s joy"). In Isaiah\'s vision of the restored community, everlasting joy replaces sorrow (Isa 35:10; 51:11; 60:15). Jesus\'s joy is his delight in the Father\'s will and the accomplishment of his mission; the invitation to share that joy is the invitation to participate in the eschatological celebration — already anticipated in the present, not deferred to the end.</p>',

    "12": '<p>"My command is this: Love each other as I have loved you" — the love command introduced as "new" at 13:34 is now presented as the singular command that encompasses all others. Jewish tradition enumerated 613 commandments (taryag mitzvot) in the Torah; various teachers proposed summaries (Hillel\'s "What is hateful to you, do not do to your neighbor," attributed in the Babylonian Talmud, Shabbat 31a; Jesus\'s own summary in the Synoptics of love of God and neighbor, Matt 22:37–40). The Evangelist\'s reduction to a single command — love each other as Christ has loved — is the most radical of these summaries.</p>',

    "13": '<p>"Greater love has no one than this: to lay down one\'s life for one\'s friends" — Greek philosophical tradition elevated self-sacrifice for one\'s <em>philoi</em> (friends) as the highest conceivable expression of love (Aristotle, <em>Nicomachean Ethics</em> IX.4, 8). The Maccabean martyrology celebrated those who died for the people and the Law as noble and vicarious (4 Maccabees especially uses the language of vicarious atoning suffering). The Stoic tradition (Epictetus, <em>Discourses</em> 2.7) similarly honored death for a friend as the limit-case of loyalty. Jesus draws on both traditions but exceeds them: he lays down his life not for worthy friends who have earned it but for disciples who will flee and deny him.</p>',

    "14": '<p>"You are my friends if you do what I command" — the condition might appear to limit friendship to the obedient. In context it functions differently: the friends-not-servants distinction is already established in v15; the condition describes what friendship looks like in practice rather than prescribing its basis. Jewish tradition had a rich set of models for covenant friendship rooted in shared fidelity: the "steadfast love" (<em>hesed</em>) of the covenant was precisely the loyalty that held when tested. The disciples\' commandment-keeping is the expression of the friendship Jesus has initiated, not its precondition.</p>',

    "15": '<p>"I no longer call you servants... I have called you friends" — the Greek distinction between <em>philoi</em> (friends) and <em>douloi</em> (slaves) was both philosophical and social. Aristotle argued that genuine friendship required equality of aim and mutual disclosure; a master and slave could not, by definition, be true friends (NE VIII.11). Jesus overturns this by disclosing to his disciples "everything I have heard from my Father" — the sharing of the patron\'s purposes that transforms slaves into friends. In Jewish tradition, Abraham was called "friend of God" (<em>philos theou</em>, Isa 41:8 LXX; Jas 2:23; also in Philo, <em>On Sobriety</em> 55–56) and Moses spoke with God "face to face, as one speaks to a friend" (Exod 33:11). The elevation of the disciples to friendship extends to all of them what had previously been the privilege of the founding covenant figures.</p>',

    "16": '<p>"You did not choose me, but I chose you" — the reversal of social logic reflects the patron-client framework in which relationships were initiated by the patron\'s sovereign choice, not the client\'s approach. The disciples did not compete for the honor of Jesus\'s attention; they were elected from the beginning (cf. 6:70: "Have I not chosen you, the Twelve?"; 13:18). The divine election theme runs through the Johannine material (6:44, 65: no one can come unless the Father draws them) and connects to the broader OT theology of Israel\'s election (Deut 7:6–8: "not because you were more numerous... but because the LORD loved you").</p>',

    "17": '<p>"Love each other" — the repetition closes the vine-and-branches section by returning to its founding command. The Evangelist\'s structure is deliberate: from the vine metaphor (vv1–11) through the friendship teaching (vv12–16) back to the single command (v17). The fruitfulness the vine metaphor describes, the intimacy the friendship teaching offers, and the love command are not separate topics but a single movement: abiding in Jesus produces the kind of love that is the community\'s definitive mark.</p>',

    "18": '<p>"The world hates you" — the word <em>kosmos</em> in the Johannine literature frequently designates the organized human order arrayed against God and his purposes (cf. 1 John 2:15–17). The hostility is structural rather than incidental: the disciples have been chosen "out of the world" (v19), creating a categorical opposition. Second Temple Jewish sectarian movements had made the same structural move: the Qumran community understood itself as the elect remnant separated from an apostate Israel and a hostile world-order. Early Christianity\'s sense of being "called out" (<em>ekklēsia</em>, assembly) drew on this precedent.</p>',

    "19": '<p>"I have chosen you out of the world" — the vocabulary of election <em>from</em> the world echoes both the OT election tradition (Deut 7:6; 14:2: Israel chosen from all the nations) and the sectarian self-understanding of the Qumran community, which described its members as the elect of God separated from the wicked. The promise is not that the disciples will leave the world physically but that they have been transferred to a different ultimate allegiance — "in the world but not of it," as the High-Priestly Prayer will put it (17:15–16).</p>',

    "20": '<p>"A servant is not greater than his master" — this saying, previously applied to the foot-washing (13:16, where it governed the disciples\' obligation to serve one another), is here reapplied to suffering: if the master was persecuted, the servant will be too. The reversal is characteristic Johannine double application: the same saying governs both the community\'s humble service to one another and its willingness to share the master\'s rejection by the world. In the Synoptics the saying appears in the mission discourse (Matt 10:24–25), where it prepares the Twelve for persecution on the road.</p>',

    "21": '<p>"Because of my name" — persecution "for the name" (<em>dia to onoma mou</em>) is persecution for bearing the identity and allegiance of Jesus. In Greek legal and religious thought, name (<em>onoma</em>) carried the full person and authority. The early church understood persecution as suffering "for the name" (Acts 5:41; 9:16; 1 Pet 4:14–16). The parallel between rejection of Jesus and rejection of the Father — "they do not know the one who sent me" — invokes the shaliach principle: to reject the agent is to reject the sender. Ignorance of the Father, the Evangelist consistently argues, is the root failure from which the world\'s hostility grows.</p>',

    "22": '<p>"If I had not come and spoken to them, they would not be guilty of sin; but now they have no excuse" — the argument reflects a Jewish category of sin distinguished by knowledge. Leviticus 4–5 differentiates between unintentional sins (committed in ignorance, atoned by specific offerings) and presumptuous sins (committed in full knowledge, for which the covenant community had no remedy). The light of Jesus\'s presence and teaching has transformed the world\'s sin from the unintentional category to the fully culpable. Paul makes a parallel argument in Rom 1:18–20: the gentiles suppress known truth, making them without excuse.</p>',

    "23": '<p>"Whoever hates me hates my Father as well" — the statement escalates the claim of v21. Rejecting the words of the shaliach (v21) is already rejecting the sender; but here the Evangelist moves to the affective dimension: hatred of the Son is hatred of the Father. The chain is positive (love for the Father expressed through love for the Son, 14:21, 23) and negative (hatred of the Son entailing hatred of the Father). The unity of Father and Son means that no attitude toward the Son can be segregated from an attitude toward the Father.</p>',

    "24": '<p>"The works no one else did" — the works argument mirrors 14:11 ("at least believe on the evidence of the works themselves"). The Evangelist has structured the entire Gospel around the signs as evidence: the blind man healed (ch. 9) explicitly provokes the question of Jesus\'s origin and authority; the raising of Lazarus (ch. 11) is the proximate cause of the Sanhedrin\'s decision to kill him (11:47–53). The signs are not neutral events that everyone interprets differently; they are evidence that implicates those who see and reject. The same logic Paul applies to the gentiles (Rom 1:20) the Evangelist applies to those who witnessed the works.</p>',

    "25": '<p>"To fulfill what is written in their Law: \'They hated me without reason\'" — the citation draws on Ps 35:19 and/or Ps 69:4 (both contain "hated me without cause"). The phrase "their Law" (<em>en tō nomō autōn</em>) rather than "the Law" appears when the Evangelist has Jesus invoke the Jewish authorities\' own scriptures as testimony against them (see also 8:17; 10:34; 19:7). The distancing phrase is not anti-Jewish per se but forensic: the scriptures they claim as their own authorize bear witness against them. The fulfillment formula ("to fulfill what is written") presents the hostility not as a historical accident but as the playing out of a pattern disclosed in advance.</p>',

    "26": '<p>"The Advocate comes, whom I will send to you from the Father — the Spirit of truth who goes out from the Father" — the dual origin of the Spirit (sent by the Son, going out from the Father) became the axis of the later filioque controversy between Eastern and Western Christianity: whether the Spirit proceeds from the Father alone (Eastern position) or from the Father and the Son (Western addition to the Nicene Creed). The Evangelist\'s primary concern is not the metaphysics of eternal procession but the authority of the Spirit\'s witness: the Paraclete\'s testimony about Jesus is authoritative precisely because it originates with both the Father and the Son, making it the divine self-attestation to the Son\'s identity.</p>',

    "27": '<p>"You also must testify, for you have been with me from the beginning" — the apostolic qualification for witness is eyewitness presence from the beginning of the ministry. The requirement of direct knowledge for valid testimony reflects both Jewish and Roman legal practice: a witness must have first-hand knowledge of what they attest (Deut 19:15–18; Num 35:30). The phrase "from the beginning" (<em>ap\' archēs</em>) mirrors 1:1 and 1 John 1:1–4, where the same phrase establishes the authority of those who "heard... saw... looked at and touched" the Word of life. The apostolic witness is not optional commentary on the Spirit\'s testimony but its necessary human medium.</p>'
  },

  "16": {
    "1": '<p>"So that you will not fall away" (<em>skandalisthēte</em>) — the verb refers to stumbling over a skandalon, a trap or obstacle that causes a fall from faith. In Jewish tradition the skandalon was often the temptation presented by external pressure — the apostasy-inducing trial that led the righteous to abandon the covenant (Ps 119:165; Isa 8:14 in its LXX rendering). The disciples\' consistent failure to understand what was happening (12:16; 13:7; 20:9) left them vulnerable to losing faith at the passion. The farewell discourse functions as an interpretive preparation: when events come that would otherwise look like defeat, the prior word will prevent a collapse of faith.</p>',

    "2": '<p>"They will put you out of the synagogue" — <em>aposynagōgos</em> appears only in John (9:22; 12:42; 16:2), suggesting it reflects a specific experience in the Johannine community\'s history. The process by which Jewish followers of Jesus were separated from the synagogue is historically debated. A plausible — though contested — connection has been drawn with the Birkat ha-Minim ("blessing against heretics"), reformulated at Yavneh ca. 85–90 CE, which added a malediction on <em>minim</em> (heretics) and <em>notzrim</em> (Nazarenes/Christians) to the synagogue Amidah prayer, making participation uncomfortable or impossible for Jewish Christians. "Anyone who kills you will think they are offering a sacrificial service to God" — the word used is <em>latreia</em> (cultic service, worship). The Phinehas tradition (Num 25:7–13) provided a model: Phinehas killed an Israelite engaging in apostasy and was rewarded with a "covenant of peace" — zeal for God expressed through execution of the apostate. Paul before his conversion described his persecution of the church in precisely these terms (Phil 3:6: "as for zeal, persecuting the church"; Gal 1:13–14; Acts 26:10–11).</p>',

    "3": '<p>"Because they have not known the Father or me" — the epistemological diagnosis repeated from 15:21. In the Hebrew prophetic tradition, failure to "know" God (<em>da\'at YHWH</em>) was not primarily intellectual but relational-covenantal: Israel\'s unfaithfulness was diagnosed as a failure to acknowledge and respond to God\'s character and acts (Hos 4:1–6; Jer 9:3–6; Isa 1:3: "The ox knows its master, the donkey its owner\'s manger, but Israel does not know, my people do not understand"). The persecutors act from ignorance of the very God whose servants they believe themselves to be.</p>',

    "4": '<p>"I have told you this so that when their time comes you will remember that I warned you" — the function of predictive teaching as a faith anchor when predictions come true is a consistent Johannine strategy (2:22; 12:16; 14:29). The act of remembering (<em>mnēmoneuēte</em>) is not passive recollection but active interpretation: the disciples will recognize the events as the fulfillment of Jesus\'s words and will thereby understand rather than misunderstand the passion. Memory of prior teaching becomes an interpretive key.</p>',

    "5": '<p>"None of you asks me, Where are you going?" — the apparent conflict with 13:36 (Peter\'s question) and 14:5 (Thomas\'s question) is resolved by recognizing that the Evangelist is describing the disciples\' interior orientation: they have been asking where Jesus is going but from anxiety about their own situation, not from concern for his destination and the glory of his return to the Father. The disciples\' grief has consumed their attention; their questions have been about themselves, not about him. The pastoral diagnosis is acute: grief turns people inward.</p>',

    "6": '<p>"You are filled with grief" — the Greek <em>lypē</em> (grief, sorrow) has left "no room" for other thoughts. The physiology of grief in ancient thought was often described as filling or occupying the heart (Ps 13:2; Prov 12:25; Isa 65:14). The full heart has no capacity for the joy Jesus is about to describe. The diagnosis sets up the turn in v7: what they experience as cause for grief is actually cause for benefit — if only they could hear it. The pastoral movement of the discourse is from grief to reassurance to joy (vv20–22).</p>',

    "7": '<p>"It is for your good that I am going away. Unless I go away, the Advocate will not come" — the counterintuitive logic finds no parallel in Second Temple Jewish eschatological expectation, which anticipated the restoration of God\'s full presence to Israel in the land and the universal outpouring of the Spirit in the messianic age (Joel 2:28–32; Ezek 36:26–27; Isa 44:3). None of this literature envisions a messianic figure departing as the necessary condition for the Spirit\'s arrival. The logic is uniquely Johannine: the Spirit\'s pervasive, universal, unbounded presence is more beneficial to the community than the localized, place-specific presence of the incarnate Son.</p>',

    "8": '<p>The Paraclete\'s forensic role — "convince/convict the world" (<em>elegchein</em>) — is a legal term for cross-examination that produces a verdict of guilt. In Greek legal practice, the <em>elenchos</em> was the formal refutation that exposed a false claim. The Paraclete functions here not merely as a defense advocate for the disciples but as a prosecuting advocate against the world\'s verdict on Jesus. This prosecutorial function was not anticipated in Jewish pneumatology, which generally described the Spirit as empowering prophecy and guiding the covenant community, not as pursuing a legal case against the world.</p>',

    "9": '<p>"Of sin, because people do not believe in me" — the Spirit\'s conviction regarding sin is not about the world\'s conventional moral failures but about the root failure: unbelief in Jesus. This reflects the Johannine understanding of sin as ultimately a relational category — failure to receive the one sent by God (1:11–12; 3:18, 36). The world\'s prosecution of Jesus as a blasphemer and criminal was itself the supreme expression of this sin; the Spirit\'s testimony reverses that verdict.</p>',

    "10": '<p>"Of righteousness, because I am going to the Father" — the Spirit\'s conviction about righteousness is the vindication of Jesus against the Jerusalem authorities\' guilty verdict. The ascension is the Father\'s verdict: by receiving the Son back into his glory, the Father declares him righteous against every charge. This is the Johannine equivalent of Paul\'s argument in Rom 4:25 ("raised for our justification") and 1 Tim 3:16 ("vindicated by the Spirit"). The world\'s judicial verdict — crucified as a criminal — is overturned by the Father\'s resurrection-and-ascension verdict.</p>',

    "11": '<p>"Of judgment, because the prince of this world now stands condemned" — the perfect tense <em>kekritai</em> ("has been judged and remains judged") presents the condemnation of the cosmic adversary as an accomplished fact, not a future event. The cross is not where Satan wins but where he is condemned — the moment that appears to be his victory is the moment of his definitive defeat (cf. 12:31: "the prince of this world will be driven out"; Col 2:15: "having disarmed the powers and authorities, he made a public spectacle of them, triumphing over them by the cross"). The Spirit\'s testimony is that the present world-order, which appears to be running on its own terms, is already under a verdict.</p>',

    "12": '<p>"More than you can now bear" — the graduated disclosure of teaching was a recognized principle in both Greek and Jewish wisdom traditions. Plato\'s image of the cave draws on the idea that eyes adjusted to darkness cannot immediately bear full sunlight. Jewish tradition recognized that Torah could not be taught all at once: "A person should not teach a student except what the student\'s mind is able to absorb" (Babylonian Talmud, <em>Pesachim</em> 3b). Paul applies the principle explicitly (1 Cor 3:2: "I gave you milk, not solid food"). The promise of the Spirit as guide to "all the truth" does not bypass the disciples\' current limitations but provides for their future completion.</p>',

    "13": '<p>"He will guide you into all the truth" — the Spirit as guide to truth participates in the Jewish wisdom tradition in which Wisdom herself was the guide: "Wisdom led [Jacob] on straight paths; she showed him the kingdom of God" (Wis 10:10). The Dead Sea Scrolls speak of God\'s spirit guiding the community into right conduct (1QH 9:32; 1QS 3:20–21). The distinctive Johannine contribution is the Christological focus: the Spirit guides into "all the truth" where "the truth" is identified with Jesus (14:6). The Spirit\'s guidance is not into propositions but into the full meaning of who Jesus is — a meaning the disciples cannot yet bear but will receive progressively after the resurrection.</p>',

    "14": '<p>"He will glorify me because it is from me that he will receive what he will make known to you" — the Spirit\'s self-effacing work, glorifying the Son rather than himself, provides an internal criterion for evaluating claimed spiritual experiences and revelations in the early community. 1 John 4:2–3 makes the test explicit: the spirit that confesses Jesus Christ has come in the flesh is from God; the spirit that denies this is not. A movement, teaching, or spiritual manifestation that draws attention to itself rather than to Christ fails the Johannine criterion. The Spirit\'s role is to make Christ visible, not to displace him.</p>',

    "15": '<p>"All that belongs to the Father is mine" — the chain of divine self-communication: the Father\'s fullness belongs to the Son; the Spirit receives from the Son and discloses to the disciples. This is the Johannine theology of revelation in its most compressed form. The movement is downward and outward — from the Father\'s eternal fullness through the Son\'s incarnate disclosure through the Spirit\'s ongoing witness to the community. Each stage is not a diminution but a fuller realization of the original fullness in a new medium.</p>',

    "16": '<p>"A little while" — the Greek <em>mikron</em> echoes Isa 26:20 (LXX): "Come, my people, enter your rooms and shut the doors behind you; hide yourselves for a <em>little while</em> (<em>mikron hoson</em>) until his wrath has passed by." The context in Isaiah 26 is the eschatological vindication of the righteous after a period of hiding and suffering. The Evangelist\'s double horizon — death and resurrection in the immediate term, the whole post-Easter era in the longer term — is consistent with the Isaiah background, where the hiding-and-emerging pattern covers both an immediate crisis and a final triumph.</p>',

    "17": '<p>The disciples\' repeated mutual questioning ("what does he mean?") reflects a realistic portrait of confused followers processing a teacher\'s difficult saying. The Evangelist has deployed this technique throughout the Gospel: Nicodemus asks "how?" (3:4, 9), the Samaritan woman asks about living water (4:11–12), the disciples misunderstand "sleep" (11:12–13), and now the inner circle cannot parse "a little while." The technique is both realistic — genuinely obscure sayings do produce confusion — and theological: understanding is consistently a post-event gift, not an in-the-moment achievement.</p>',

    "18": '<p>The repeated question — "What does he mean by \'a little while\'? We don\'t understand" — is not just literary characterization. It models the experience of readers who are equally perplexed. The Evangelist has the disciples verbalize what the reader may be feeling, creating an identification before the explanation in verses 20–22 resolves the confusion. The technique is a form of pastoral pedagogy: the perplexity is named and validated before it is addressed.</p>',

    "19": '<p>"Jesus saw that they wanted to ask him" — the attribution of omniscient knowledge to Jesus (knowing what the disciples wanted to ask without being told) is consistent with the pattern established in chapter 2 (2:24–25: "He did not need any testimony about mankind, for he knew what was in each person"), chapter 4 (4:17–18, the Samaritan woman), and chapter 11 (11:4: knowing the purpose of Lazarus\'s illness from a distance). The Evangelist consistently presents Jesus as operating from a perspective that exceeds normal human information — a feature that characterizes both the divine wisdom tradition (Wis 7:23; Prov 8) and the specifically Johannine Christology.</p>',

    "20": '<p>"You will weep and mourn while the world rejoices" — the contrast maps onto the crucifixion: the disciples flee and mourn (20:11: Mary at the tomb, weeping); the Jerusalem authorities and the crowd that had called for crucifixion celebrate a victory (19:15, 21). The reversal — grief turned to joy, the mourning disciples becoming the joyful resurrection witnesses — is the Gospel\'s narrative arc in miniature. The Evangelist has already narrated the weeping (20:11–18) and the joy (20:20: "the disciples were overjoyed when they saw the Lord") before the reader returns to this promise.</p>',

    "21": '<p>The childbirth image was a standard Jewish eschatological metaphor for the suffering that precedes the messianic age. The "birth pangs of the Messiah" (<em>hevlei ha-mashiah</em>) was a recognized term in early rabbinic thought for the period of tribulation preceding the new age (later codified in tractate <em>Sanhedrin</em> 97a). Isaiah uses the image extensively (Isa 26:17; 66:8–9; Jer 22:23; Mic 4:9–10). The Qumran Thanksgiving Hymns (1QH 3:7–12) use birth-pang language for the community\'s suffering that precedes eschatological vindication. Jesus draws on a widely available eschatological register: the disciples\' grief at his death is the labor; the resurrection appearance is the birth; the joy is complete and the pain is forgotten.</p>',

    "22": '<p>"No one will take away your joy" — the permanence of eschatological joy echoes Isaiah\'s repeated promises about the restored community: "everlasting joy will be on their heads" (Isa 35:10; 51:11), "I will create Jerusalem to be a delight and its people a joy" (Isa 65:18–19). The joy the disciples will have after the resurrection is not a temporary emotional relief but the inauguration of the permanent eschatological reality — a foretaste of the joy that will be complete when the kingdom comes in its fullness.</p>',

    "23": '<p>"In that day you will no longer ask me anything" — the contrast is between the present state of persistent perplexed questioning and the clarity of understanding that comes after the Spirit\'s arrival. The prophetic promise of Jer 31:34 is the closest OT parallel: "No longer will they teach their neighbor, or say to one another, \'Know the LORD,\' because they will all know me, from the least of them to the greatest." The Evangelist does not claim that the disciples will know everything — only that the confused, questioning uncertainty of the farewell discourse will be resolved by a knowledge that comes through the Spirit.</p>',

    "24": '<p>"Until now you have not asked for anything in my name" — literally accurate: the disciples have prayed in Jesus\'s presence (as in 11:41–42) but have not yet prayed in his name, because the full weight of what that name means — the post-resurrection disclosure of Jesus as the risen Lord — has not yet been given. "Ask and you will receive, and your joy will be complete" — the connection of prayer and joy continues the eschatological register: the joy promised in v22 is the joy of those who know how to ask and receive from the Father in the Son\'s name.</p>',

    "25": '<p>"I have been speaking figuratively (<em>en paroimiais</em>)" — <em>paroimia</em> is distinct from <em>parabolē</em> (parable): it suggests riddle-like or proverbial speech, the compressed wisdom-saying that requires interpretation. The book of Proverbs (<em>mishle</em> in Hebrew, whose Greek title was <em>Paroimiai</em>) gives the form its name. The announcement that "a time is coming when I will no longer use this kind of language but will tell you plainly about my Father" anticipates the post-Easter encounters where the risen Christ speaks with a clarity that the disciples had not experienced during the ministry (Luke 24:25–27, 44–47; John 20:19–29).</p>',

    "26": '<p>"I am not saying that I will ask the Father on your behalf" — the potential misreading of the Paraclete promises (that Jesus will petition a reluctant Father on the disciples\' behalf) is preemptively corrected. The Father is not reluctant; he is not a third party who must be persuaded to bless the disciples. The chain of love runs from the Father himself through the Son to the disciples, not from the disciples through a reluctant divine hierarchy. The intercessory role of Jesus (as in 1 John 2:1; Rom 8:34; Heb 7:25) is not a circumvention of the Father\'s love but a participation in it.</p>',

    "27": '<p>"The Father himself loves you because you have loved me" — the claim that the disciples have direct access to the Father\'s love, not merely mediated access through Jesus\'s intercession, is striking in the context of Second Temple Jewish prayer. Intercessory structures were common: the Psalms regularly invoke God through appeals to the righteous ancestors; 2 Macc 15:12 describes Jeremiah interceding posthumously; the Dead Sea Scrolls expected angelic mediators. The Evangelist\'s insistence is that the disciples\' love for Jesus places them in the Father\'s own love, requiring no mediating figure beyond the Son who has already bridged the distance.</p>',

    "28": '<p>"I came from the Father and entered the world; now I am leaving the world and going back to the Father" — the four-part summary of the Incarnation (origin, descent, departure, return) is one of the Gospel\'s clearest statements of its Christological schema. It was without parallel in mainstream Jewish messianic expectation, which envisioned the Messiah as a human figure from the line of David (Mic 5:2; Ps Sol 17:21), not as a heavenly figure descending from and returning to the divine realm. Some Second Temple Jewish apocalyptic traditions described figures ascending to heaven (Enoch, Elijah, Moses) but not a preexistent figure descending and then returning — the schema is distinctively Johannine.</p>',

    "29": '<p>"Now you are speaking clearly and without figures of speech" — the disciples\' relief at apparently plain speech reflects a real feature of the discourse: after the enigmatic "little while" passages, the direct four-part statement of v28 reads like simplicity itself. The Evangelist will show (v32) that the disciples\' confidence is premature — they think they understand and believe, but the passion will scatter them. The gap between the disciples\' self-assessment and their actual readiness is itself a pastoral lesson: confidence in understanding does not guarantee faithfulness under pressure.</p>',

    "30": '<p>"You know all things and do not even need to have anyone ask you questions" — the disciples\' claim echoes the Johannine presentation of Jesus\'s omniscient knowledge of human thought (2:24–25; 4:17–18; 6:64; 11:14). But the disciples are reasoning from a single instance (v19: Jesus anticipating their unspoken question) to a universal conclusion — the move from sign to confession that the Gospel has consistently traced. Their confession "this makes us believe that you came from God" is genuine but not yet fully tested; verse 32 will expose its limits.</p>',

    "31": '<p>"Do you now believe?" — the question (or possible exclamation) does not dismiss the disciples\' confession but checks its depth. The Evangelist\'s pattern of inadequate confession followed by testing and deeper understanding runs from the first disciples (1:35–51: genuine but incomplete initial faith) through Nicodemus (genuine but hidden faith) through Martha (genuine confession without full comprehension) to here. The disciples\' "now we believe" will be put to the test within hours, and found wanting — but not finally.</p>',

    "32": '<p>"You will be scattered, each to your own home. You will leave me all alone" — the scattering of the flock when the shepherd is struck echoes Zech 13:7 ("Strike the shepherd, and the sheep will be scattered"), a verse the Synoptic accounts of the Last Supper make explicit (Mark 14:27; Matt 26:31). The Zechariah text places the shepherd\'s striking in the context of a divine act of purification that produces a refined remnant (Zech 13:8–9); the scattering is not the end of the story but the crisis that precedes restoration. The disciples\' individual retreat "to his own home" (<em>eis ta idia</em>) contrasts with Jesus who goes "to the Father." Their departure is flight; his is return.</p>',

    "33": '<p>"In this world you will have trouble (<em>thlipsin</em>). But take heart! I have overcome the world" — <em>thlipsis</em> was the standard term in Jewish eschatological literature for the tribulation that precedes the end — the "birth pangs" of v21 in a different register. The closing assertion "I have overcome the world" uses the perfect tense (<em>nenikēka</em>): the victory is already accomplished, stated before the passion that achieves it. This is the Johannine realized eschatology at its most concentrated — the outcome declared before the events. The command "take heart" (<em>tharseite</em>) appears in the Synoptics in other crisis moments (Mark 6:50 and Matt 14:27: walking on water; Matt 9:2: healing the paralyzed man) — the tone of the one who has already assessed the situation from the vantage of its resolution.</p>'
  }
}


def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'john')
    merge_comm(existing, JOHN)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'john', existing)
    print('John 14–16 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
